entry.title: Crash Fix for a Prerendering Page's RFH UAF upon activation
entry.content:
This CL avoids the use a raw pointer to ref. a Prerendering Page's

RenderFrameHost (RFH) as this tend to be destroyed after activation of

the prerendering page, which lead to Use After Free (UAF) crashes from

downstream calls.



This CL propose the collection of static details and hold those instead

of a pointer to the RFH.

entry.title: [rust] Expand all archives in remote link.
entry.content:
Prior to this change, the remote linking procedure would ask the linker

to make a list of all the linkable object files using

-Wl,-plugin-opt=thinlto-index-only=$out

$out here is an .rsp file which is intended to be passed straight into

the linker later.



When presented with .a archives or equivalent, this would list invalid

filenames within the rsp file, and thus caused linker errors.



This is a known limitation of the remote LTO procedure:

https://discourse.llvm.org/t/running-distributed-thinlto-without-thin-archives/52261.

and the standard workaround seems to be to extract object files from

archives prior to performing the indexing step. That's what this CL

does.



This wasn't previously important, because only one non-thin archive

was included (a clang runtime .a), and as this was machine code not

bitcode, none of its members underwent this treatment.

However, the standard output format for a Rust "crate" (a Rust

compilation unit) is an .rlib, which is a (non-thin) .a in disguise, and

thus we have to cope with non-thin archives properly.



This CL expands the .a or .rlib into individual object files before

proceeding. The script already coped with "thin archives"; that is,

lists of references to existing files on disk, so this change expands

that existing logic to cope with all types of archives, actually

extracting files if necessary. (Either way, such archives are

wrapped in --start-lib, --end-lib switches which means the expanded

list of .o files is equivalent to including the archive directly.)



This requires us to switch from the previously python-coded .a

parser to using the full power of llvm-ar, so tht we can cope with

both thin and regular archives.



Alternatives considered:

(a) amend lld so that the output of thinlto-index-only no longer

produces invalid filenames. For the reasons discussed in the

LLVM thread above, this is deemed unlikely to work.

(b) persuade rustc to generate thin archives instead of regular

archives. This seems unlikely to work unless the component .o

files are retained on disk somewhere after construction of the

.rlib file - this could be a future optimisation

(c) post-process the output of thinlto-index-only before using it

as linker input (e.g. by quoting each line). This could work

but is more complex, and it doesn't avoid the need to extract

each file at some point.

(d) Extract the files just as we're doing here, but instead

using steps within the generated ninja file. This would have

benefits in parallelizing the extraction and in avoiding

unnecessary rebuilds for unchanged inputs, but did not work

in practice because the process of generating the ninja file

itself depends upon the nature of each .o file (bitcode or

otherwise).

(e) Expand the existing parser to cope with regular .a archives

as well as thin archives, instead of calling out to llvm-ar.

Although this would be slightly quicker, the complexity does

not seem obviously merited, since linking time is dominated

by other factors.



As part of this change,

* The --ar-path argument has become the first required=True

argument to this script, so the overall argument parsing

has been slightly simplified.

* Suitable test code has been added. NB that on some platforms

it may be easier to run the test code if you

also have

https://chromium-review.googlesource.com/c/chromium/src/+/4672673

entry.title: [Viz] CHECK that frame from ReserveVideoFrame() uses per-plane sampling
entry.content:
FrameSinkVideoCapturerImpl creates a VideoFrame via

VideoFramePool::ReserveVideoFrame() and later has to decide whether to

tell CopyOutputRequest() to use multiplanar format or not for this

frame. If this frame could have kSharedImageFormatExternalSampler, we

entry.title: Use unique trace ids for console timings with different names
entry.content:
Console timing events can be used to measure the duration of a task in

JS and the recorded data is added to the performance panel timeline data

via trace events. A console.time('name') event dispatches a trace begin

event and a console.end('name') dispatches a trace end event.



Before this cl, the trace id used to dispatch console timing events was

a pointer to the process and, as a consequence, was shared within

console timing events in the same process, regardless of the console

timing name. This was problematic because the trace id is used to match

trace begin and end events. Meaning that the trace end event dispatched for a given console.end will always be matched with the latest trace begin event that was dispatched. However, there is no guarantee that a console.end call is intended to end the last console.time call. Instead they should be matched by name, which this CL achieves by using the timing name the API was called with in the id of the trace event.



Co-authored-by: jacktfranklin@chromium.org

Fixed: 1455582

entry.title: Properly balance test begin and end markers in Blink perf test runner
entry.content:
The test runner relies on adding JS console marks at the beginning and

end of each test iteration using the console timing API [1] [2]. However

the markers added in `measureFrameTimeOnce` are not balanced because it

doesn't add an end marker after the last run.



This isn't a problem at the moment because the last opening event is

closed by another end marker added at the very end of the test runner

execution [3]. Note that the remaining opening event is closed by an end

marker with a different name, which intends to close a different open

event, this is a bug.



However, with https://crrev.com/c/4665408 , this will be a problem

because that CL intends to make begin markers closable only by end

markers with the same name (it fixes the bug mentioned before). As such,

the end marker at the end of the test runner execution will not close

the marker that remained open on the last run of `measureFrameTimeOnce`.

This issue can be seen in the test failures of the cited CL [4].



To fix this problem, a call to add the test marker is added inside a rAF

callback, to ensure the opening event is closed and that it's closed in

the next frame (as the previous logic intended).



Finally, the expectations file for the test

`measure-frame-time-expected` is re-baselined, since it depends on the

number of calls to rAF in `measureFrameTimeOnce`





[1] https://source.chromium.org/chromium/chromium/src/+/main:third_party/blink/perf_tests/resources/runner.js;l=327



[2] https://source.chromium.org/chromium/chromium/src/+/main:third_party/blink/perf_tests/resources/runner.js;l=336



[3] https://source.chromium.org/chromium/chromium/src/+/main:third_party/blink/perf_tests/resources/runner.js;l=279



[4] https://ci.chromium.org/ui/p/chromium/builders/try/linux-rel/b8776410189769730753/overview

entry.title: gpu: Handle GL_RGB_YCRCB_420_CHROMIUM src in DoCopyTextureInternal().
entry.content:
This CL allows GetFragmentShaderId() in

gles2_cmd_copy_texture_chromium.cc to support GL_RGB_YCRCB_420_CHROMIUM

as a source format thus avoiding a NOTREACHED(). This NOTREACHED() being

hit was discovered as part of the out-of-process video decoding (OOP-VD)

experiment. It happens on MT8173 ChromeOS devices when doing display

capturing with webrtc.



> More context:



The reason this NOTREACHED() wasn't hit without OOP-VD is that we create

the source textures with an internal format of GL_RGBA in the non-OOP-VD

path for MT8173 [1]. If I change that to use GL_RGB_YCRCB_420_CHROMIUM,

I hit the same NOTREACHED() without OOP-VD. Note that this non-OOP-VD

path on MT8173 doesn't use SharedImage, unlike the OOP-VD path.

The problem of the original CL is that if the pinned container

is cleaned up before a pinned window, it can lead to

use-after-free of `container_`.

destruction of `container_` or ResetWindowPinningState() can

happen first.

The parent container of a pinned window is set up for pinned mode

With this CL, the container is tracked in ScreenPinningController

entry.title: Fetch teacher assignment info per course work
entry.content:
This is intended as an optimization when fetching student submission

lists for teacher glanceables. Instead of fetching them in a single

request for all courses (which would presumably produce a large list

with multiple pages), fetch student submissions per course work items.

This should be more parallelized (given that submissions for different

course work items can be done concurrently, and result in less

paginated result lists), avoid fetching submissions for irrelevant

course work, and enable future optimizations (to avoid student

submission fetches for older course work items).



This is done by adding `fetch_submissions` parameter to

`GlanceableClassroomClientImpl::FetchCourseWork()`. When this parameter

is set, handling a course work page would be extended to also fetch

submissions for course work items in that page. This complicates how

course work callback is passed around (given that student submission

fetches from a page may overlap with a request to fetch the next

course work page). Requests are not all done serially, so just passing

the callback from one request to another will not work.

This CL introduces a `CourseWorkRequest` class, which caches the

request callback, and tracks all pending course work page requests.

The callback is called once data (including student submissions) from

all pages has been fetched.



This also:

* merges GlanceablesClassroomStudentAssignment and

GlanceablesClassroomTeacherAssignment classes into a single class.

* Changes the values in `student_submissions_` map from vector of

student submissions, to a map from a course work ID to a vector of

student submissions. Note that this mapping was created ad hoc

either way once all student submissions and course work items

had been fetched.

entry.title: webauthn: don't upgrade UV for registration on platform authenticators
entry.content:
Chrome has long upgraded the WebAuthn registration requests that would

create a discoverable credential to require user verification, even

though the spec technically allows user-presence-only registration.



This was done because we didn't want to promote uv-less, single-factor

sign-ins using security keys, well before platform authenticators were

common, or passkeys had existed.



These days, sites can commonly register passkeys on a platform

authenticator with UV=preferred to avoid triggering a system password

prompt on devices where convenient UV factors (biometrics, short PINs)

are unavailable. But Chrome's "auto upgrade" to uv=required interferes

with that. The original motivation for why Chrome did this with security

keys doesn't really apply to platform authenticators (where the device

needs to be in an "unlocked" state anyway to register). Hence, align

with other browsers' implementations here and allow UP-only registration

of discoverable credentials **for platform authenticators**. (No change

for registering on external authenticators such as security keys.)



Fixed: 1459436
